nodes.title: Model and lora Loading
widgets_values:
3 ways to load the models

Load diffusion model
This loads a normal model (non gguf) 

Unet Loader (GGUF)
This allows loading gguf models.

UnetLoaderGGUFDisTorchMultiGPU
This allow you to load a gguf and force offload some or all of the model to the ram.  Lower vram use, but slower.  This allows longer or larger videos at expense of speed.

Virtual ram gb - this is used to set how much of the model is sent to ram to be loaded when needed.

The GGUF Q8 is about 18-19gb.  
So setting 10 sends about 10 gb to ram and tries to load the rest in vram.

Setting 16 will mostly load the whole model into ram, and only load what it can into vram as it renders.
This works well but slows things down.

This number is determined by how large the model you are using is, and how much ram you have.
your model size - virtual ram gb = how much it tries to put into vram.



LORA

Causevid is a 8 step lora for wan.
This is loaded in the model only loader at 0.8 strength default

Accvid lora and movigen lora here
https://huggingface.co/Kijai/WanVideo_comfy/tree/main


This lora can oversaturate videos color.  Lower strength or lower steps if you notice this.

Other loras
Any text to video lora (for the size of the model) works. 
Image to video loras do not work here.



Ensure the model / clip / vae are connected wtih the options you want to use.

nodes.title: Ref Image
widgets_values:
This area is a crop for the ref image

This and your prompt shape what it inpaints.

You can have any image here with the face you want to inpaint, it can enhance a face or change it.

This auto crops 2 ref images, one for head including hair, and one for face

Ref Box detect detects the face and crops around it,
You can pad the face and head separate, ensure the previews show what you want copied.

Face restore is NOT needed but i like it.  It sharpens the face some but can remove small details, up to you if you use it.  It can be safely removed from the flow.

Head preview should show hair, 
Face preview just needs the face area but try to give it context of what its inpainting.

nodes.title: Cut outs and controls
widgets_values:
Here is the cut out area were we cut out the face to work on.

Size of cutout 
- This is the size sent to the sampler.  
- 240-1024 works, just keep it within your vram, this is square. 480 is default, its usually good enough.

Erode Dilate
- This changes the inpaint area
- down to make it smaller, up to make it bigger.

Controled Inpaint or Blank inpaint
- If you made a control at the start to use, you should enable the control here.
- Controls are NOT needed unless you need to keep facial movements.
- blank offers best quality.

Strength of blank inpaint
- 0.7-1  (recommended 1)
Controls how strong the inpaint is, lower this to keep some of the original.

Preview to the right shows the cutout, and the inpaint area. 
Ensure this is correct before you continue.

nodes.title: Inpainting
widgets_values:
Positive and negative

USE BOTH
If getting something you dont want negative it out.
Positive should be what you want.

Yes... this can nudify people... 

Control strength
-This is how strong the ref image is to the inpaint.  1.0 probably best.

Default steps is 6, can do as many as you want here, 4-12 is usually best.

Eular and Simple used defaults

Others
UNIPC Beta
DDIM ddim uniform (different results)

nodes.title: Paste Back Blending
widgets_values:
This pastes back the cutout video to the original.

Blend mask fix lets you 
erode/dilate - positive bigger, negative smaller

Feather mask
feathers any edges of the mask that touch the edge of the cutout box, if your box however touches the edges of the video you can remove the feather on that side.

Blur
Can adjust this 2-20 in either kernal or sigma.
This determines the blur in the blend back
- Too strong (large) and you will blur out what you are pasting back
- too weak (small) and you will notice seems where the cutout happened.

nodes.title: Controled Inpaint
widgets_values:
You can use depth or open pose to control the video mask area.

You can blend the two controls to better control the strength of depth. 
Set blend factor to blend at differnet ratios, 0.15 is 85% openpose, 15% depth. 

If not using this you can use white, white is good for faces unless you need to keep movements.

nodes.title: Start Image
widgets_values:
Extending works by using the last frame from the previous video to start the next.

Copy (clipspace) the previous last frames from the right, to the load start image.  

This will crop that start image in the same spot as the first frame of the new video to match for both the face and head.

You need to enable the use of these for them to work.  THis just loads the image, you need to enable the options to the right for them to work.

I dont know how well this works i tested it to make sure it did not crash. But not sure if it blends well.

nodes.title: Masking
widgets_values:
I know, i know everyone hates masking, even me.

Well i have made this as simple as i could. 

This has 3 masking options

1. BBox masking
 - this just works, and most of the time you dont need to go further than this.
 - This is fast and usually automatic. 
 - Video Box Detect is all you need to tune what it detects
 - If background faces are detected you can use the Drop Mask Smaller Than

2. Segmentation masking
 - This blends better sometimes and sometimes worse than bbox only.
 - this has the same options as bbox, only this masks the object inside the bbox.

3. Sam 2 masking
 - This lets you mask anything, but its less stable sometimes and usually requires the stabablize option.


Once you make the mask of the face you have a few options

Padding
-Lets you cut out further from the head area to get more context for blending, (skin colors) Make this smaller if using stabalize.

Fill Holes or remove Isolated
- This lets you fix slightly bad masks.  Bbox should not need this but sometimes sam2 or segs can.
- fill holes does just that, fill holes in the mask and remove isolated can help remove small white detections that are smaller than this.

Stabalize Cut out
- this is used to change the cutouts to be uniform, meaning the same area is cut from each frame.
- this has the effect of camera stabalization.  
- Without it, the cutout box can jump between frames due to changes in the masking, causing the input control video to be "jumpy" Wan has a hard time following this jumpy action as its not a natural camera motion.  Sam 2 is most vunerable to this.
- Its best to try not using this.  But if needed it can stabalize the mask area.
- this can cause the cutout to cut much furter from the face, loosing details.

Enable the preview to the right to see the cutout and mask

Green is the inpaint area, and yellow is the cutout area
Make sure there is enough space around the inpaint area to have context to what its inpainting.
Make sure these are correct before you continue

If the yellow box is wonky, check the mask, its probably got something else detected and its boxing it too.  Either that or the padding is too large for the video.
